34:48.300 --> 34:49.630
audience.

34:49.630 --> 34:52.630
"Not at all, Dr. Krauss,"
Teller began.

34:52.630 --> 34:55.230
"I'm listening to every word
you're saying.

34:55.230 --> 34:58.270
I don't carry a pad of paper
or a cell phone, but as

34:58.270 --> 35:02.000
a magician, I always have
my deck of cards with me.

35:02.000 --> 35:06.800
I use that deck and my knowledge
of magic to take notes.

35:06.800 --> 35:10.130
Please allow me to recap
what you've covered so far."

35:10.130 --> 35:12.470
Then, Teller fanned
the cards out.

35:12.470 --> 35:16.330
"You know, Lawrence, you're a
very well known atheist.

35:16.330 --> 35:19.730
As I look over the faces
of the cards, I notice there's

35:19.730 --> 35:22.070
no God among them.

35:22.070 --> 35:24.200
The universe of my deck,
like the universe

35:24.200 --> 35:29.700
of your speech, contains kings,
queens, millions of number

35:29.700 --> 35:33.900
combinations and, well,
even a couple of jokers, but no

35:33.900 --> 35:36.530
God can be found."

35:36.530 --> 35:40.800
Teller motioned to the professor
and Lawrence Krauss, he stood up

35:40.800 --> 35:43.100
right there in the audience.

35:43.100 --> 35:45.870
Teller explained that he would
riffle down the deck

35:45.870 --> 35:49.970
and the professor should yell,
"Stop!," then select a random

35:49.970 --> 35:53.000
particle from the universe
of Teller's deck.

35:53.000 --> 35:55.030
Well, Teller riffled.

35:55.030 --> 35:58.030
Professor yelled...

35:58.030 --> 36:00.370
